 new legal citations and record series, update department/division titles which may have changed, remove obsolete record titles and revise retention periods, as needed. This update is presented annually to the City Council for review and approval. The 2017 Retention Schedule (Attachment A), reflects all changes and highlights new records that were added. The 2016 version of the Retention Schedule (Attachment B) shows strikethroughs of items that were deleted and retention periods that were changed. The revised retention schedule went through an extensive review by division managers and department heads and was approved by the City Attorney and City Clerk.", "Records destruction, which is also part of the program, requires written authorization from the department head, City Attorney, and City Clerk. When there is a possibility of litigation or an audit, related documents scheduled to be destroyed according to the Retention Schedule will be kept for a minimum of one year after the lawsuit/audit is settled or until deemed appropriate for destruction by the City Attorney and City Clerk.", "Financial Impacts and Budget Actions", "There is no immediate financial impact or budget action necessary as a result of the recommended action."]}, {"Title": "Bid Award for the Purchase of Sodium Hypochlorite for Water Treatment", "Department": "Public Works, Water Resources", "Sponsors": null, "Category": "03. Consent Calendar", "Recommendations": "Staff recommends that the City Council:1. Award Bid #4289 to Olin Corporation, a California-based company, as the primary vendor for the purchase of sodium hypochlorite for the Arcadia Water Treatment Plant and Charnock Well Field site; JCI Jones Chemicals, Inc., a California-based company, as the secondary vendor for the purchase of sodium hypochlorite for the Arcadia Water Treatment Plant and Charnock Well Field site; and Waterline Technologies, a California-based company, for purchase of sodium hypochlorite for the Santa Monica Urban Runoff Recycling Facility (SMURRF);2. Authorize the Purchasing Services Manager to issue a purchase order with Olin Corporation for sodium hypochlorite in the amount not to exceed $120,000 for one year, with four additional one-year renewal options to extend at mutually agreeable price adjustments ranging from -10% to +10%, for a total not to exceed $600,000, with future year funding contingent on Council budget approval;3. Authorize the Purchasing Services Manager to issue a purchase order with JCI Jones Chemicals, Inc. for sodium hypochlorite in the amount not to exceed $20,000 for one year, with four additional one-year renewal options to extend at 5% increases, for a total not to exceed $110,513, with future funding contingent on Council budget approval; 4. Authorize the Purchasing Services Manager to issue a purchase order with Waterline Technologies for sodium hypochlorite in the amount not to exceed $20,000 for one year, with four additional one-year renewal options to extend at increases between 4% to 10%, for a total not to exceed $115,748, with future funding contingent on Council budget approval.", "Body": ["Executive Summary", "As part of a multi-stage treatment process to provide a safe and reliable supply of water, the City uses sodium hypochlorite to disinfect potable water produced at the Arcadia Water Treatment Plant and the Charnock Well Field site, and non-potable water used for landscaping and other purposes at the Santa Monica Urban Runoff Recycling Facility (SMURRF). In May 2017, the City solicited bids for 5,000-gallon tanker truck deliveries of sodium hypochlorite solution for the Arcadia and Charnock sites, and smaller 60-gallon deliveries to the SMURRF. Five bids were received. Staff recommends splitting the bid award to the lowest cost providers of sodium hypochlorite for each site.", "For the Arcadia and Charnock sites, Olin Corporation, the lowest bidder, would be the primary vendor in an amount not to exceed $600,000 over a five-year period. In order to avoid production stoppages due to delivery issues from the primary vendor, JCI Jones Chemicals, the second-lowest bidder, would be designated as the secondary vendor in an amount not to exceed $110,513 over a five-year period. For the SMURRF, Waterline Technologies, the lowest bidder, would supply sodium hypochlorite in an amount not to exceed $115,748 over a five-year period.", "Background", "The City uses a multi-stage treatment process to produce approximately 8,600 acre-feet of potable water per year at the Arcadia Water Treatment Plant and the Charnock Well Field site located in West Los Angeles (1228 S. Bundy Drive and 11375 Westminster Avenue, respectively); and up to 175 acre-feet of non-potable water per year at the Santa Monica Urban Runoff Recycling Facility (SMURRF) located at 1625 Appian Way. Water from these facilities is supplied to approximately 18,000 Santa Monica accounts including 29 \u201cpurple pipe system\u201d recycled water accounts used primarily for landscaping and indoor non-potable purposes. In order to comply with Federal and State regulations, 12% to 15% sodium hypochlorite (NaOCl) solution is applied to local groundwater and urban runoff as part of the disinfection process to kill harmful pathogens. Sodium hypochlorite is used on a large scale for surface purification, bleaching, odor removal and water disinfection.", "The Arcadia Water Treatment Plant and Charnock Well Field site have historically required 25 to 40 5,000-gallon tanker truck deliveries of bulk sodium hypochlorite solution per year. With the City\u2019s commitment to becoming water self-sufficient by 2020, it is anticipated that increased production and treatment of local groundwater would require additional water treatment chemicals in future years.", "Due to the lack of on-site chemical storage at the SMURRF, tanker truck deliveries cannot be accommodated. Instead, the City typically requires deliveries in 15-gallon carboy containers with four containers delivered 30 to 40 times per year. Due to the smaller quantities and more frequent deliveries required, chemical vendors supplying bulk products via tanker truck have historically not been able to offer deliveries to this site. Sodium hypochlorite demand is also expected to increase at SMURRF in future years in concert with the City\u2019s plan to expand recycled water production. Key upcoming projects include SMURRF reverse osmosis improvements as part of the City\u2019s Sustainable Water Infrastructure Project, expansion of the City\u2019s purple pipe system by 1,000 feet per year, and construction of a 1.6 million gallon storage tank near the Santa Monica Pier to supply storm water to the SMURRF as part of a Clean Beaches Initiative project.", "Discussion", "In May 2017, the City issued a two-part bid seeking bulk tanker truck deliveries of sodium hypochlorite solution for the Arcadia Water Plant and Charnock Well Field Site; and smaller deliveries of four 15-gallon carboys at a time for the SMURRF. Bidders were offered the opportunity to bid on one or both parts.", "Due to the critical need for sodium hypochlorite at the Arcadia Water Plant and Charnock Well Field site, staff anticipated selecting two or more providers for these locations in order to ensure continuity of supply and avoid any potable water production shutdowns which would necessitate importing water from Metropolitan Water District at a cost of $979 per acre-foot.", "Vendor Selection", "On May 23, 2017, the City published Notices Inviting Bids to furnish and deliver sodium hypochlorite to the Arcadia Water Plant, Charnock Well Field site and SMURRF in accordance with City specifications. The bid was posted on the City's on-line bidding site, and notices were advertised in the Santa Monica Daily Press in accordance with City Charter and Municipal Code provisions. A total of 19 vendors downloaded the bid. Five bids were received and publicly opened on June 5, 2017, per Attachment A.", "Bids were evaluated based on the criteria in SMMC 2.24.072, including price, previous experience, ability to deliver, quality of product, and compliance with City specifications.", "For provision of bulk 5,000-gallon loads of sodium hypochlorite to the Arcadia Water Plant and Charnock Well Field site, Olin Corporation offered the lowest pricing of $0.572 per gallon and JCI Jones Chemicals offered the second-lowest pricing of $0.60 per gallon, which are both less expensive than the $0.629 per gallon charged by current vendor Olin Corporation. Olin Corporation has supplied the City with sodium hypochlorite satisfactorily for the past three years and JCI Jones Chemicals has supplied the City satisfactorily with water treatment chemicals including sodium bisulfite since 2011. Due to the critical need for sodium hypochlorite solution for the production and disinfection of potable water supplied to Santa Monica customers in compliance with Federal and State water treatment regulations, staff recommends awarding this portion of the bid to two vendors to ensure continuity of supply. Based on these criteria, Olin Corporation, the lowest bidder, is recommended as the best bidder and primary supplier of sodium hypochlorite to the Arcadia Water Plant and Charnock Well Field site. JCI Jones Chemicals, the second lowest bidder, is recommended as the secondary supplier of sodium hypochlorite to these locations.", "Should Olin Corporation not be able to supply the Arcadia Water Plant or Charnock Well Field site with sodium hypochlorite in the timeframe or amounts required by the City, orders would be placed with JCI Jones until Olin Corporation could supply the necessary quantities.  Olin Corporation has offered renewal year options with price adjustments ranging from +10% to -10% mutually agreed to with the City. Over five years, it is anticipated that the amount purchased would not exceed $600,000. Secondary vendor JCI Jones Chemicals, has offered renewal year options with 5% annual price increases. Over five years, it is anticipated that the amount purchased would not exceed $110,513.", "For provision of 15-gallon carboy containers of sodium hypochlorite to the SMURRF, Waterline Technologies offered the lowest pricing of $2.48 per gallon. Waterline Technologies has satisfactorily supplied the City with sodium hypochlorite since 2008. Based on these criteria, Waterline Technologies, the lowest bidder, is recommended as the best bidder to supply sodium hypochlorite to the SMURRF. Waterline Technologies has offered renewal year options at annual price increases ranging from 4% to 10% annually. Over five years, it is anticipated that the amount purchased would not exceed $115,748.", "Financial Impacts and Budget Actions", "The purchase order to be awarded to Olin Corporation is for an amount not to exceed $120,000. The purchase order to be awarded to JCI Jones Chemicals is for an amount not to exceed $20,000. The purchase order to be awarded to Waterline Technologies is for an amount not to exceed $20,000. Funds are available in the FY 2017-18 budget in the Public Works Department. The purchase orders will be charged to the following accounts:", "Olin Corporation", "25672.544011", "$50,000", "25673.544011", "$70,000", "Total:", "$120,000", "JCI Jones Chemicals", "25672.544011", "$8,000", "25673.544011", "$12,000", "Total:", "$20,000", "Waterline Technologies", "31661.566631", "$20,000", "Future year funding is contingent on Council budget approval."]}, {"Title": "Bid Award for the Purchase of Two Compressed Natural Gas Sign Trucks and One Compressed Natural Gas Asphalt Tool Truck", "Department": "Public Works, Street & Fleet Services", "Sponsors": null, "Category": "03. Consent Calendar", "Recommendations": "Staff recommends that the City Council:1. Award Bid #4278 to Raceway Ford, a Michigan-based company, for the purchase and delivery of two Compressed Natural Gas Sign Trucks;2. Authorize the Purchasing Services Manager to issue a purchase order wi